WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:13.240
In 1983, NASA sent Sally Ride into space as the first American woman to ever enter into

00:00:13.240 --> 00:00:15.120
orbit.

00:00:15.120 --> 00:00:19.799
In the lead-up to her launch, the engineering team at NASA was very hard at work to ensure

00:00:19.799 --> 00:00:22.639
that everything would go off without a hitch.

00:00:22.639 --> 00:00:29.440
So at some point before the big day, the all-male team came to Ride to ask her if a sufficient

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:36.080
number of tampons for a week-long mission was 100 tampons.

00:00:36.080 --> 00:00:41.439
Ride simply responded, no, that would not be the correct number.

00:00:41.439 --> 00:00:45.520
When pressed for more information, she told them that they could cut that number in half

00:00:45.520 --> 00:00:48.599
and it would still be way too many.

00:00:48.599 --> 00:00:52.279
I love this story for a variety of reasons.

00:00:52.279 --> 00:00:55.639
One of them is that I just find it fun to imagine what led up to the moment where they

00:00:55.639 --> 00:00:58.599
finally landed on the number 100.

00:00:58.599 --> 00:01:00.840
Were they all sitting around a round table?

00:01:00.840 --> 00:01:02.439
How long were they talking?

00:01:02.439 --> 00:01:03.439
These are engineers.

00:01:03.439 --> 00:01:10.120
Did they do research on the absorbency per tampon and do back-of-the-envelope calculations?

00:01:10.120 --> 00:01:14.239
Another reason I love this story is I think it's really well-suited to communicate this

00:01:14.239 --> 00:01:21.320
idea that even the most well-intentioned group of people will often do a laughable job of

00:01:21.320 --> 00:01:25.480
trying to meet the needs of another group that they are not part of.

00:01:25.480 --> 00:01:29.360
I think about how much smoother that process would have gone if there was just one menstruating

00:01:29.360 --> 00:01:31.919
person on that engineering team.

00:01:31.919 --> 00:01:36.320
This really drives home for me the idea that to truly make something that meets someone's

00:01:36.320 --> 00:01:43.160
needs, someone who has those needs themselves must be part of the development process.

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:48.480
And as you may have guessed from the title of my talk, I'm not here to talk about tampons.

00:01:48.480 --> 00:01:52.919
So in recent years, there's been a growing awareness, understanding, and acceptance of

00:01:52.919 --> 00:01:56.519
the importance of technology accessibility.

00:01:56.519 --> 00:01:59.839
And as we all know, technology doesn't just create itself.

00:01:59.839 --> 00:02:03.320
Data doesn't analyze itself, or at least not yet.

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:08.559
So we have this process of an initial developer, contributor, maintainer, who supports the

00:02:08.559 --> 00:02:12.639
creation of a tool or who is doing the data science themselves.

00:02:12.639 --> 00:02:19.080
So they then produce an output, whether that's an app or a dashboard, a piece of software,

00:02:19.080 --> 00:02:24.279
and then that subsequently ends in the hands of a stakeholder or end user.

00:02:24.279 --> 00:02:29.440
And in most of this dialogue so far, we tend to focus at the end on that end user.

00:02:29.440 --> 00:02:32.720
And we generally do this by focusing in on the output stage.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:36.720
We do this by asking ourselves questions like, can someone who is colorblind distinguish

00:02:36.720 --> 00:02:38.639
the features of this graph?

00:02:38.639 --> 00:02:43.520
Or have I included sufficient alt text for someone who requires nonvisual access to this

00:02:43.520 --> 00:02:45.000
information?

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:49.720
But I'm here to insist that this is the wrong place for us to be focusing if our goal is

00:02:49.720 --> 00:02:54.320
to avoid being like that all-male engineering team at NASA.

00:02:54.320 --> 00:02:59.360
Instead of focusing primarily on the experience of the end user, we need to look further upstream

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:03.759
and divert our attention toward the experience of the programmer or data scientist.

00:03:03.759 --> 00:03:09.839
We need to work to reduce unnecessary barriers for disabled coders and continue to support

00:03:09.839 --> 00:03:16.080
their ability to continue to use and contribute to open source projects.

00:03:16.080 --> 00:03:20.080
And so to do this, we need to think about the tools, packages, languages, programs,

00:03:20.080 --> 00:03:24.440
et cetera, that data scientists and developers depend on in their daily work.

00:03:24.440 --> 00:03:28.320
We need to figure out how we can improve the accessibility of these tools so that we can

00:03:28.320 --> 00:03:33.479
ensure fewer structural barriers to the continued participation and flourishing of disabled

00:03:33.479 --> 00:03:36.199
members of the open source community.

00:03:36.199 --> 00:03:39.839
In the remainder of my talk, I'm going to discuss some simple steps that can be taken

00:03:39.839 --> 00:03:44.320
to begin improving the accessibility of open source projects.

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:49.639
Importantly, these are steps that can be taken by absolutely anyone and don't require having

00:03:49.639 --> 00:03:54.520
any depth of knowledge in accessibility or web accessibility.

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:58.679
As a result of that, I'm not going to get into any of the particularly technical aspects

00:03:58.679 --> 00:04:01.160
of technology accessibility.

00:04:01.160 --> 00:04:05.160
In the link to my slides, which I'll bring up again at the end, I also have a collection

00:04:05.160 --> 00:04:08.039
of resources that I am also continuing to add to.

00:04:08.039 --> 00:04:15.039
So if you come back in the following weeks, there's going to be more and more resources.

00:04:15.039 --> 00:04:19.600
So imagine that you are renovating your kitchen and everything's going perfectly until you

00:04:19.600 --> 00:04:20.839
come across some issue.

00:04:20.839 --> 00:04:25.200
So you do some Googling, you try to figure out what's going on, and eventually you think

00:04:25.200 --> 00:04:29.040
you figured it out and it seems like you can solve it yourself if you just get your hands

00:04:29.040 --> 00:04:31.480
on a specific power tool.

00:04:31.480 --> 00:04:35.279
So you go online and spend some significant effort researching and selecting the right

00:04:35.279 --> 00:04:39.839
tool, making sure it has specific set of features and capabilities that you need.

00:04:39.839 --> 00:04:45.559
You order it, and unfortunately, once it arrives, it has plug type F, which is used commonly

00:04:45.559 --> 00:04:50.119
throughout much of Europe, but you're located in the U.S., and therefore your outlets only

00:04:50.119 --> 00:04:53.160
accommodate type A or B plugs.

00:04:53.160 --> 00:04:56.799
It would have been great if this information was included in the product description, but

00:04:56.799 --> 00:04:57.799
it wasn't.

00:04:57.799 --> 00:05:02.440
In fact, it's not present in the description of almost any tool that you can find online.

00:05:02.440 --> 00:05:06.880
So your best bet is to just keep buying new ones and trying them to see if they work.

00:05:06.880 --> 00:05:09.760
If you're thinking that this sounds like it would be an incredibly frustrating way to

00:05:09.760 --> 00:05:15.480
get something done, you're right, and it's also the reality for many disabled data scientists

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:19.239
and programmers when it comes to trying out open source tools in order to solve their

00:05:19.239 --> 00:05:20.760
programming problems.

00:05:20.760 --> 00:05:26.679
In this metaphor, we should be thinking of the power tool as a package or IDE or tool,

00:05:26.679 --> 00:05:30.519
and the plug outlet compatibility is accessibility, right?

00:05:30.519 --> 00:05:35.839
So it's the IDE that someone wants to work in, and the outlet is their screen reader.

00:05:35.839 --> 00:05:39.760
And if you don't in a lot of instances, they have no way of knowing whether or not the

00:05:39.760 --> 00:05:44.480
two will work together until after they've downloaded it and tried it.

00:05:44.480 --> 00:05:48.839
And unlike an incompatible plug, you can't just go on Amazon and buy a travel adapter

00:05:48.839 --> 00:05:52.119
and just circumvent the whole thing with accessibility.

00:05:52.119 --> 00:05:55.640
So this brings me to the first thing we can do, which is create accessibility docs.

00:05:56.079 --> 00:06:01.760
What I mean when I say this is creating documentation that helps individuals quickly assess whether

00:06:01.760 --> 00:06:09.000
something meets not only their technical requirements, but crucially also their accessibility requirements.

00:06:09.000 --> 00:06:13.140
This can look like a lot of different things, like just a high-level status of the accessibility

00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:14.440
of the tool.

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:19.959
Importantly, you can just say that you don't know, even it is unknown how compatible this

00:06:19.959 --> 00:06:24.000
is with screen readers or we haven't done any research into the accessibility of this

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.519
is significantly more informative than saying nothing at all.

00:06:29.519 --> 00:06:34.200
You can also create start curating a list of known accessibility problems.

00:06:34.200 --> 00:06:36.200
And you can highlight accessibility features.

00:06:36.200 --> 00:06:40.160
Some of these might be things that are specific to accessibility, but there are probably some

00:06:40.160 --> 00:06:46.920
that already exist, like keyboard shortcuts or various options for error handling.

00:06:46.920 --> 00:06:51.160
So once you establish what you do already know or not know about accessibility, you're

00:06:51.160 --> 00:06:53.320
going to want to set up a way to get further information.

00:06:53.320 --> 00:06:56.720
So you're going to create a forum for feedback.

00:06:56.720 --> 00:07:01.760
One of the easiest ways to do this is to create an accessibility issue template or label.

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:03.480
And this serves a variety of purposes.

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:05.799
One is it serves a really valuable signal.

00:07:05.799 --> 00:07:10.679
Under status quo, when already facing a lot of other barriers for their participation,

00:07:10.679 --> 00:07:15.160
a disabled programmer has to then try to assess whether or not it's actually worth it to put

00:07:15.160 --> 00:07:18.920
the time and effort to create a valuable reproducible example.

00:07:19.239 --> 00:07:24.799
Because it's not clear whether or not the maintainers of that project actually care

00:07:24.799 --> 00:07:26.480
and want to fix this.

00:07:26.480 --> 00:07:29.839
I would hope that everybody that's in this room is in the group of people that would

00:07:29.839 --> 00:07:33.720
want to, but there is still a lot of ableism within tech.

00:07:33.720 --> 00:07:37.160
And there are a lot of people who think it's really just not that important to focus on.

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:38.959
So this gets you information.

00:07:38.959 --> 00:07:45.220
Because now people know, okay, it's worth it to try to put in, you know, this information.

00:07:45.220 --> 00:07:48.799
It also elevates the importance of accessibility and helps us with culture change.

00:07:48.799 --> 00:07:53.480
So we can start thinking of problems with accessibility as bugs and not as add-on features

00:07:53.480 --> 00:07:58.440
that we think of after the initial development of the product is complete.

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:02.359
And it's crucial for identifying issues that are specific to the particular tool.

00:08:02.359 --> 00:08:06.440
Some issues with accessibility are going to come up again and again and again.

00:08:06.440 --> 00:08:09.720
But some are just going to be really niche and you're not going to know unless you're

00:08:09.720 --> 00:08:12.119
told about your specific project.

00:08:12.119 --> 00:08:16.480
Now, if you're thinking that these examples are, like, cool, but they're mostly just setting

00:08:16.480 --> 00:08:21.040
the stage for improving accessibility and you want to start doing something to actually

00:08:21.040 --> 00:08:26.320
improve things, or maybe you're not a maintainer of a project and you want to be a contributor,

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:31.839
but you don't really feel like you have as much leeway to do some of these earlier steps,

00:08:31.839 --> 00:08:36.320
then I suggest that you work on improving technical documentation.

00:08:36.320 --> 00:08:37.320
And okay.

00:08:37.320 --> 00:08:42.400
I know writing documentation isn't exactly most people's favorite parts of the job.

00:08:42.400 --> 00:08:43.400
You know?

00:08:43.400 --> 00:08:46.200
Maybe there would be fewer people in the room if I had highlighted that this talk was mostly

00:08:46.200 --> 00:08:50.760
going to be about documentation in the abstract.

00:08:50.760 --> 00:08:55.840
But I'm hoping that we can manufacture some excitement by displaying just how huge of

00:08:55.840 --> 00:08:59.359
a barrier poorly accessible documentation can be.

00:08:59.359 --> 00:09:03.520
So let's say you're trying to get an overview of some sort of complex process in order to

00:09:03.520 --> 00:09:06.880
better understand something you're building or trying to debug.

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:11.400
So you bring up documentation for, say, the conceptual architecture of this tool.

00:09:11.400 --> 00:09:15.520
I've done that for an actual technical documentation page.

00:09:15.520 --> 00:09:18.559
And I'd like for us to take a moment to hear what the experience would be like with a screen

00:09:18.559 --> 00:09:19.559
