00:14:54.539 --> 00:14:59.039
I'll just sort of pull up on this slide.

00:14:59.039 --> 00:15:03.179
And with issues, you can make it for something specifically you'd like to fix or just for

00:15:03.179 --> 00:15:04.179
auditing.

00:15:04.179 --> 00:15:09.080
So make an issue for yourself to look at the alttext if you don't know right away if any

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:11.099
of it is good or not.

00:15:11.099 --> 00:15:14.739
I suggest you set a reminder for yourself to do this.

00:15:14.739 --> 00:15:19.359
Put it in your phone, add something to your calendar to do tomorrow while later tonight

00:15:19.359 --> 00:15:20.799
while waiting for your flight.

00:15:21.799 --> 00:15:24.239
And I assure you, you're not gonna want to forget to do this.

00:15:24.239 --> 00:15:30.599
And that's because as an extra piece of motivation, I have designed a custom hex sticker associated

00:15:30.599 --> 00:15:32.039
with my talk.

00:15:32.039 --> 00:15:36.000
But the only way to get one is to tag me in the comments of a pull request or an issue

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:38.239
or email me a screenshot, something like that.

00:15:38.239 --> 00:15:40.760
So I have a limited number of them.

00:15:40.760 --> 00:15:45.320
If you're here in person, you can try to come find me once you're done to get your sticker.

00:15:45.320 --> 00:15:49.719
I also know the conference ends in a few hours and there's a lot of people watching online.

00:15:49.719 --> 00:15:53.700
So if you can't find me in person, I'll make my best effort to coordinate mailing these

00:15:53.700 --> 00:15:57.000
out to as many people as I can until I run out.

00:15:57.000 --> 00:16:00.400
So thank you so much for your attention, and I look forward to getting to see the first

00:16:00.400 --> 00:16:03.400
steps you all take to starting to commit to change.

00:16:04.200 --> 00:16:12.679
Thank you so much, Rose.

00:16:12.679 --> 00:16:16.960
I'll also say, if you want to do a dplyr or tidyr technical documentation improvement,

00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:19.080
I will happily merge that.

00:16:19.080 --> 00:16:22.200
Then you can get your sticker.

00:16:22.200 --> 00:16:24.039
We have one question in the Slido.

00:16:24.039 --> 00:16:29.000
What would you recommend to incorporate into visualization packages to make them more accessible?

00:16:29.000 --> 00:16:32.000
And maybe is there anything beyond just alt text?

00:16:32.000 --> 00:16:33.200
Yeah.

00:16:33.200 --> 00:16:35.960
So one thing...

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:39.359
Another thing I didn't touch on is accessibility for people who are colorblind.

00:16:39.359 --> 00:16:43.679
So one thing that could be really great for visualization packages is to change default

00:16:43.679 --> 00:16:46.080
color settings so that they are...

00:16:46.080 --> 00:16:49.280
You want to make accessibility the easy thing to do, not the hard thing to do.

00:16:49.280 --> 00:16:54.919
So everywhere we should be making it, you know, easy to make sure, you know, if you're

00:16:54.919 --> 00:17:00.320
not thinking about it, you shouldn't have to think about it.

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:06.280
There should also be easy ways to add, like, figure text, which is true of most.

00:17:06.280 --> 00:17:11.040
And on my external resources, I will be adding some more resources about how to actually

00:17:11.040 --> 00:17:15.680
write good alt text for visualizations, because that's a tricky skill to master.

00:17:15.680 --> 00:17:23.199
Hadley, do you remember what Mine uses to, like, overlays over the image to make sure

00:17:23.199 --> 00:17:24.199
that it's, like, colorblind-friendly?

00:17:24.199 --> 00:17:25.199
Do you remember what that thing is called?

00:17:25.199 --> 00:17:26.199
There's some cool technology.

00:17:27.199 --> 00:17:31.280
There's some cool technology to make sure that your pictures are colorblind-friendly

00:17:31.280 --> 00:17:32.280
out there.

00:17:32.280 --> 00:17:34.239
They, like, overlay on top of the images themselves.

00:17:34.239 --> 00:17:38.079
I don't know much about, like, colorblind-related, but since you mentioned overlays, one thing

00:17:38.079 --> 00:17:39.400
I will mention is...

00:17:39.400 --> 00:17:43.400
Because I think everybody in the disability community would be mad if I didn't.

00:17:43.400 --> 00:17:47.239
Is that if you're creating a website or something like that where you're gonna host your documentation,

00:17:47.239 --> 00:17:51.199
anything like that, if you see a product, there's ones called, like, AccessiBe or things

00:17:51.199 --> 00:17:55.560
like that that are overlays that say they'll fix your documentation or, I'm sorry, fix

00:17:55.560 --> 00:17:58.479
your web accessibility, you shouldn't use them.

00:17:58.479 --> 00:18:02.359
They're under a lot of lawsuits right now, because they actually make accessibility worse

00:18:02.359 --> 00:18:04.459
for a lot of people.

00:18:04.459 --> 00:18:10.040
So people have developed plugins to disable them, because using them actually makes websites

00:18:10.040 --> 00:18:11.040
more inaccessible.

00:18:11.040 --> 00:18:16.079
So if it sounds too good to be true, like, a quick fix like that, it probably is.

00:18:16.079 --> 00:18:20.680
Are there any existing, like, any kind of templates that you can use for creating good

00:18:20.680 --> 00:18:23.680
accessible documentation that you know of?

00:18:23.680 --> 00:18:24.959
Yes.

00:18:24.959 --> 00:18:25.959
So I have...

00:18:25.959 --> 00:18:32.760
In the external resources, I have there a couple different style guides, examples, and

00:18:32.760 --> 00:18:33.760
yeah.

00:18:33.760 --> 00:18:34.760
Things of that nature.

00:18:34.760 --> 00:18:35.760
Great.

00:18:35.760 --> 00:18:36.760
Thank you so much.

00:18:36.760 --> 00:18:37.760
Yep.

00:18:37.760 --> 00:18:37.760


